<div class="entry">
  <div class="entry-title">Pwnagotchi — Deep Reinforcement Learning for WiFi Pwning</div>
  <div class="entry-meta">Personal Project · 2024</div>

  <div class="project-images">
    <figure>
      <img src="/images/pwnagotchi.jpg" alt="Pwnagotchi — Raspberry Pi Zero W with e-ink display">
      <figcaption>The unit — Raspberry Pi Zero W running the A2C agent, e-ink face on the front</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    I got into this because I kept asking a question I couldn't fully answer: how does AI
    actually improve a security attack? Not in theory — in practice, with real hardware,
    in the real world. Pwnagotchi was the most honest answer I could find.
    It's also just a genuinely strange and compelling thing to build.
  </p>
  <p>
    I built the whole thing from scratch — assembled the Raspberry Pi Zero W, flashed the
    custom Pwnagotchi image, configured the network interfaces, tuned the agent parameters,
    and got it running in the wild. The device roams passively, listens to wireless traffic,
    and captures WPA handshakes — the cryptographic material you need to attempt an offline
    password crack. What makes it more than just a script is the learning layer on top:
    an <strong>A2C (Advantage Actor-Critic)</strong> reinforcement learning agent that
    observes the environment and adjusts the device's behavior over time — how aggressively
    it deauthenticates clients, how it prioritizes networks — getting better the more it's
    exposed to. The e-ink display on the front shows a small face. It looks satisfied when
    it captures something. It has moods. It is, objectively, a strange pet.
  </p>

  <h3>What it's actually capturing — the WPA 4-way handshake</h3>
  <p>
    To understand why the handshake matters, you need to understand what it contains.
    When a client connects to a WPA2 network, neither side sends the password over the air.
    Instead they run a 4-message exchange — the 4-way handshake — that proves both sides
    know the password without ever transmitting it:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Message 1</strong> — The access point sends ANonce, a random number, to the client.</li>
    <li><strong>Message 2</strong> — The client generates its own SNonce, derives the PTK
      (Pairwise Transient Key) from the password-derived PMK combined with both nonces and
      both MAC addresses, then sends SNonce back alongside a MIC — a cryptographic signature
      that proves it holds the right key material without revealing it.</li>
    <li><strong>Message 3</strong> — The AP independently derives the same PTK, verifies the
      MIC, then sends the GTK (Group Temporal Key, for broadcast traffic) encrypted under the PTK.</li>
    <li><strong>Message 4</strong> — The client confirms. Both sides install their keys.
      The 802.1X controlled port opens and traffic flows.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Pwnagotchi captures Messages 2 and 3 — specifically the MIC and the nonces.
    With those in hand, an attacker can run an offline dictionary attack: hash each candidate
    password the same way the protocol would, reconstruct the MIC, and check if it matches.
    No need to be on the network. No need to decrypt live traffic. The handshake is enough.
  </p>

