<div class="entry">
  <div class="entry-title">Creality 3D Printer — Firmware & Hardware Upgrade</div>
  <div class="entry-meta">Personal Project · 2022</div>
  <p>
    This started as frustration. Prints were warping, first layers were inconsistent, and manually
    tramming the bed before every job was getting old. But once I opened the machine up, it turned
    into something more — I wanted to actually understand the hardware, learn to solder, get
    comfortable with embedded firmware, and stop treating the printer as a black box.
    That itch took me a lot further than just fixing the bed leveling.
  </p>

  <h3>Firmware — custom Marlin 2.x build</h3>
  <p>
    Stock Creality firmware has no support for the probe, so I had to compile
    <strong>Marlin 2.x</strong> from source using PlatformIO against the board's specific
    configuration files. This meant navigating the Marlin config headers, enabling
    <code>AUTO_BED_LEVELING_BILINEAR</code> with a 5×5 probe mesh, mapping the
    <code>BLTOUCH</code> signal pin correctly, and retuning <code>PIDTEMP</code> /
    <code>PIDTEMPBED</code> constants with M303 auto-tune cycles. Getting it to actually
    compile and flash without bricking the board was the most nerve-wracking part —
    there's no undo on a bad flash. It worked first try.
  </p>

  <h3>Hardware — 3D Touch probe & soldering</h3>
  <p>
    Mounted a 3D Touch probe (BLTouch-compatible) on the hotend carriage. The probe fires a
    steel pin down to physically touch the bed at each of the 25 mesh points, giving the
    firmware a real height map instead of assuming the bed is flat (it never is).
    The 5-wire harness (GND, VCC, GND, IN, OUT) needed to be routed through the cable chain
    and terminated at the mainboard — which meant soldering the signal wire onto the correct
    pad, since the stock board doesn't expose a clean probe header. First time doing
    board-level soldering on a live project. Z-offset was then dialed in using the
    paper-gap method and live baby-stepping through a test first layer until it was right.
  </p>

  <h3>Electronics & cable management</h3>
  <p>
    While the control box was open I rerouted everything properly —
    <strong>braided PET mesh sleeving</strong> over all wire bundles, no free-hanging
    conductors, strain relief on every connection point. Partly for reliability
    (bare wires chafe against the frame under constant vibration), partly because it
    looked embarrassing before. Checked all stepper driver voltages with a multimeter
    while I was in there.
  </p>

