<div class="entry">
  <div class="entry-title">Liquid Desiccant Air Conditioner (LDAC)</div>
  <div class="entry-meta">Senior Design Project · University of Bahrain · May 2021</div>
  <p>
    The LDAC is my Senior Design Project, built with my team at the University of Bahrain.
    It was awarded <strong>best project in the Mechanical Engineering department</strong> for
    2021, and received the <strong>Ebrahim Khalil Kanoo Award for Engineering Excellence</strong>.
  </p>

  <div style="text-align:center; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <iframe
      width="560"
      height="315"
      src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/g01GOKKW8NY"
      title="LDAC demo video"
      frameborder="0"
      allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
      allowfullscreen>
    </iframe>
  </div>

  <p>
    The LDAC combines an evaporative chiller with a liquid desiccant dehumidifier. The dehumidifier
    uses a CaCl₂ solution that absorbs moisture from the air, allowing the cooling unit to operate
    efficiently in a humid environment like Bahrain's. The evaporative cooler then lowers air
    temperature through water spray interaction.
  </p>
  <p>The project was executed in sequence:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>COMSOL simulation to confirm system cycle feasibility before implementation</li>
    <li>Preliminary CAD model in Autodesk Inventor for visualization and engineering drawings</li>
    <li>Physical model manufactured with Single Point Plastics</li>
    <li>Assembly with selected pipe fittings, pumps, and fan based on serviceability constraints</li>
    <li>Experiment conducted to validate simulation — measuring flow rate, temperature, and relative
      humidity throughout the LDAC cycle</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The dehumidifying unit reduced relative humidity by <strong>43.3%</strong>, delivering a
    <strong>4× improvement in COP</strong> over the evaporative unit alone. Under a 45% CaCl₂
    concentration with a superior dehumidification process, the potential COP improvement
    reaches <strong>9×</strong>.
  </p>

